{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651599"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:25:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:25:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18474"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18474"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.12,0.04,0.73,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11203"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78530"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11203"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18474"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63871"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6653"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26018"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26025"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26905"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78530"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring foetal development, the circulatory system contains several unique structures that allow blood to bypass the non-functioning lungs and receive oxygenated blood from the placenta. These structures normally close shortly after birth. One such structure is the ductus arteriosus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of this structure in the foetal circulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Connects portal vein to inferior vena cava","Allows blood flow between right and left atria","Connects umbilical vein to inferior vena cava","Connects pulmonary artery to aorta","Connects superior vena cava to pulmonary vein"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Econnects pulmonary artery to aorta\u003C/strong\u003E (image) is the correct description of the ductus arteriosus, which is a vital foetal structure that allows most of the blood from the right ventricle to bypass the non-functioning lungs and flow directly into the descending aorta.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConnects portal vein to inferior vena cava\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a feature of foetal circulation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllows blood flow between right and left atria\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the foramen ovale, not the ductus arteriosus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConnects umbilical vein to inferior vena cava\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the ductus venosus, which allows oxygenated blood from the placenta to bypass the liver\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConnects superior vena cava to pulmonary vein\u003C/strong\u003E - No such connection exists in foetal circulation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter birth, the ductus arteriosus normally closes within the first few days of life as pulmonary circulation becomes established. Its remnant in adults is known as the ligamentum arteriosum. A patent ductus arteriosus can cause respiratory problems.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ductus arteriosus connects the pulmonary artery to the aorta in fetal circulation, allowing blood to bypass the lungs.","The foramen ovale allows blood to flow directly from the right atrium to the left atrium in fetal circulation.","The ductus venosus allows oxygenated blood from the umbilical vein to bypass the liver and flow directly into the inferior vena cava."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cPatent ductus ateriosus\u201d by BrownCow is under\u00a0Public Domain. \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Patent_ductus_arteriosus.svg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63871"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18474"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21383"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21383"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JVKKIwhY6c47W6XcpqAG6W4Si2tulN.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JVKKIwhY6c47W6XcpqAG6W4Si2tulN.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":458}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63871"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T10:17:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T10:18:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11203"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78530"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior",